  "prompt": "What happens to a photon after it hits the retina of my eye?",
  "response": "When a photon hits the retina of your eye, here's what happens:\n\n1. The photon is absorbed by specialized cells called photoreceptors (rods and cones)\n\n2. The absorption triggers a chemical reaction that changes the shape of a molecule called rhodopsin\n\n3. This molecular change creates an electrical signal through a process called phototransduction\n\n4. The electrical signal is transmitted through the optic nerve to the visual cortex in the brain\n\n5. The brain interprets these signals as visual information, allowing you to perceive light, color, and images\n\nThe specific details vary between rod and cone cells:\n- Rods are more sensitive and responsible for vision in low light\n- Cones detect color and function best in bright light\n- Different types of cones are sensitive to different wavelengths (colors)\n\nAfter the photon is absorbed, its energy is effectively \"used up\" in triggering the chemical reaction, and it ceases to exist as a distinct photon.",
